      <h1>A Reformed Hacker, an AI Copilot, a Catamaran Purchase and an Idea</h1>

      <p>I'm a British software engineer running my third startup out of New York. After 25 years in California, I moved back to the UK and I'm getting ready to do something I never thought I'd say out loud — wind down, stop working, buy a catamaran, and go on a massive adventure, slowly circumnavigating the world with my wife, starting in 2027.</p>

      <p>But old habits die hard.</p>

      <h2>How I got here</h2>

      <p>At my company, <a href="https://crashoverride.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Crash Override</a>, I've been spending a lot of time using AI to speed up our engineering. Agentic coding, building specialist agents, Claude as a co-pilot — the whole nine yards. And in my spare time, I've been building apps that keep turning out <em>better</em> than the ones I use day-to-day.</p>

      <p>It started with cycling. I'm an avid cyclist, and for years I'd been juggling a grab bag of tools — GPS route planners, weather apps, race predictors, fitness trackers — none of which talked to each other. So I built a single app that rolled them all together, ran on both the web and my phone, and used AI to actually make intelligent decisions. Each feature worked better than the individual tools it replaced, and when combined into a single app, it became far, far better. It genuinely made my cycling more enjoyable.</p>

      <p>Then I started planning the catamaran purchase.</p>

      <h2>Sailing tech looks like cycling tech did a decade ago</h2>

      <p>As I've been learning about solar systems, navigation, passage planning and energy management, I've realised that the state of sailing technology looks eerily similar to where cycling technology was a decade ago — an industry that was also, ironically, dominated by Garmin.</p>

      <p>Fragmented tools. Clunky interfaces. Apps that haven't been meaningfully updated in years and are getting left behind as things like AI come along. Sound familiar?</p>

      <p>So I had an idea. And the idea is simple.</p>

      <h2>The idea</h2>

      <p>Find a community of sailors who want technology that's better than what they have today. Better as in it actually works properly. Better as in it does things their current apps can't. Better as in they're beautifully designed and a pleasure to use, not a burden. Better as in it embraces modern technology, especially AI. Better as in it evolves and improves at the pace of driverless cars and not oil tankers. And better as in it's free. That's everyone, right?</p>

      <p>Then give them a place to hang out. Somewhere to share ideas, request features, report what's broken, and help shape what gets built next. Basically, create a user community.</p>

      <p>As people hear about what's being built, start using it and feel they are part of it — all done in an open, public and transparent way — things rapidly go from being prototypes, a bit rough around the edges, to far better than the commercial tools on the market. Suddenly a community is building tools they actually want and love, rather than tools they have to use and feel they have to put up with. I've seen it happen before.</p>

      <p>This model of development is called open-source, and it's something I've been involved with for over two decades. I created <a href="https://owasp.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OWASP</a> in 2001, which now has over 40,000 community members, and I've seen first-hand what happens when you get a vibrant community behind a shared problem. My friend and co-founder at Crash Override, John Viega, developed a cryptographic algorithm that you're using right now in your web browser or phone, and in a previous life accidentally created the unsubscribe link — we all owe him for that one. We released a part of our commercial product called <a href="https://chalkproject.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Chalk</a> as open-source. You can achieve amazing things. Building software this way doesn't have the overhead of how companies work, so you develop dramatically faster, work directly with users instead of through bureaucratic layers, and — honestly — it's just more fun.</p>

      <p>You publish the code on the internet for free, so that anyone can, if they want, contribute or extend it. This also ensures no commercial company will ever screw the users down the road by suddenly charging for it or taking away things people rely on. It ensures the use of it will be free, forever. And before you think open-source is for hippies, Crash Override is backed by Google Ventures.</p>

      <h2>This is for sailors, not developers</h2>

      <p>Now, most people don't care about any of that, and that's fabulous. They just want tools that work, and work better than what they have today. The more passionate sailors who use this stuff and tell me what's wrong with it, the better it gets, and everyone wins. I'm not building software for myself — I'm brand new to sailing and I have everything to learn. Software that's better for experienced sailors will be better for me too. We're on the same side of this. That's what this will hopefully become — a collective, a community hub, a home for the tools that come out of it, and more importantly, the people who use and love them.</p>

      <h2>Some of these are just my homework</h2>

      <p>I should be upfront. Right now, some of these tools are really just me figuring things out in public. I need to understand how much solar my catamaran actually needs, so I built a solar planner. I need to understand energy budgets, so I'm building tools to model them. I'm learning VHF radio, so I built an AI-powered VHF emulator to practise with. Think of it as my homework, made interactive and shared in case it's useful to someone else.</p>

      <p>But the vision and roadmap is far more ambitious. I have ideas to use advanced AI and real scientific research to build planning tools that are genuinely better than anything that exists — optimal route planning that factors in live weather and tidal patterns, not just waypoints on a chart. Trip planning that combines weather forecasts, tidal windows, live crowd data from Google, community reviews, and local knowledge — so it knows the anchorage with the great taverna, when it's going to be rammed with charter boats, and the best time to arrive. Or the passage timing that avoids the orcas attacking boats in the Med. Planning tools that actually <em>plan</em>, rather than just displaying data and leaving you to figure it out. More time enjoying the sailing and the experience, less time doing chores and getting disappointed.</p>

      <p>This isn't technology for the sake of it. Think about what Google Maps did to navigation — it didn't just digitise the A-Z, it fundamentally changed how you move through the world. Think about what WhatsApp did to staying in touch. Think about what Waze did by letting a community of drivers make the experience better for every other driver. The technology disappeared and the experience just got better. That's the goal here. Not more screens, more data, more complexity. Just better sailing.</p>

      <h2>What this isn't</h2>

      <p>To be completely clear, this is not and will never be a commercial startup. I've been there, done it, and I'm not doing it again. I'm paying for all the hosting and operating costs myself. Open-source and community software has been good to me over the years, and this is a way of giving back. I also just love communities — doing stuff like this in the past has been some of the most fun I've had. If it stops being fun, I'll just stop doing it.</p>

      <h2>Come join me</h2>

      <p>This only works if people show up. Here's how to get involved:</p>

